        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We selected band 7 because it provides the bluest wavelength among all offered 
standard configurations. Since the main objective is to detect the continuum 
emission from the disk, the correlator setup makes use of full continuum 
sensitivity. However, we can get a bonus on the potential scientific outcome 
of the project by also measuring the CO 3-2 line at 345 ghz (free of charge) 
in one of the basebands with a spectral resolution below 1 km/s without any 
loss in the continuum sensitivity. We have chosen the spectral line observing 
mode with baseband 1 in the signal band centered at the rest frequency of the 
CO 3-2 line covering a bandwidth of 1.875 GHz with a resolution of 0.98 km/s 
(after averaging 2 channels). Baseband 2 has been centered 1.8 GHz above 
baseband 1 to cover 1.875 GHz at a resolution 27.2 km/s. The other two 
basebands have been centered at the corresponding image band frequencies. 
The image band was selected 12 GHz above the signal band to minimize the 
possible effects of the atmospheric water vapor line at 325 GHz. The final 
continuum will be obtained by averaging all channels except for those of 
the CO line in case it is detected.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
The two components of the system are separated by 8 arcsec. With the requested 
angular resolution and angular scale we will be able to identify whether the 
debris disk is around the primary or the planet or both.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
This is an exploratory observation to detect thermal emission from the dust 
of a debris disk that is likey present in the planetary system J1256-1257. 
With a flux density of 80 microJy, a disk with a mass of 0.05 Mlunar and 
15 K can be detected around either the planet or primary component at the 
distance of the system. For a 3-sigma detection of the continuum emission, 
we require an rms of 26.7 microJy. We based the sensitivity requirement on 
the continuum flux.

See also the explanation given for the correlator configuration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
